    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:eb9fca3e-34d8-48d9-8212-a197d7a16f03",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 65-year-old Czech man who presents for urologic follow-up after a prior diagnosis of prostate cancer. He says he was diagnosed years ago and underwent radical prostatectomy, and he understands that “prostate cancer” and “malignant neoplasm of prostate” refer to the same condition. Although he still considers his overall condition very good and remains independent, he now admits to several lower urinary tract symptoms that have gradually become more noticeable over time. He describes daytime urinary frequency, urgency, a weaker urinary stream than before, mild burning discomfort with urination, and occasional difficulty fully emptying his bladder. He also reports intermittent episodes of visible blood in the urine, which prompted him to pay closer attention to follow-up.\n\nHe is a large-framed older man with longstanding hypertension managed with several oral medications. He also has obesity and a history of metabolic syndrome with impaired fasting glucose, which developed over the years. In conversation he is calm but attentive to medical terminology, particularly after seeing the phrase “malignant neoplasm of prostate” in his records and wondering whether it implied a new change rather than the original cancer diagnosis. He monitors his health closely and is motivated to keep regular appointments.\n\nAt this visit, {patientName} is focused mainly on surveillance but also on understanding whether his urinary symptoms could reflect postoperative changes or recurrent disease. He understands that PSA should be checked at regular intervals after radical prostatectomy and that a PSA value above 0.2 ng/mL after surgery may indicate biochemical failure. He denies severe pain, fever, or complete inability to pass urine, but says there have been brief episodes of hesitancy and near-retention that were uncomfortable. He lives a fairly routine life, values staying independent, and relies on close family support for transportation to specialist visits.\n\nHe is retired from technical work and spends much of his week at home with his spouse, doing household tasks, reading newspapers, and taking regular walks for exercise. His activity level is decent but reduced somewhat by age, weight gain, and concern about needing quick access to a toilet when away from home. He does not appear acutely ill during the encounter, but the urinary complaints are bothersome enough that he wants them documented clearly."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:80c0603e-a418-4222-922e-fa6fcae9920d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports a past diagnosis of prostate cancer in 2006 and says the tumor was described with a Gleason score of 10/10. He underwent radical prostatectomy and afterward received intermittent leuprolide and bicalutamide, though these were part of his cancer treatment history rather than current background medicines. He recalls being told that regular PSA checks are necessary after surgery.\n\nBefore his cancer diagnosis, he had several features associated with increased prostate cancer risk, including older age at presentation, obesity, a sedentary work pattern, and a family history of prostate cancer. He states that his father had prostate cancer later in life, and a paternal uncle also had the disease. He additionally reports a family history of related malignancy, with his mother having had breast cancer. His other medical history is notable for longstanding hypertension treated with lisinopril, atenolol, and amlodipine, as well as obesity and impaired fasting glucose consistent with metabolic syndrome, both relevant to overall cancer risk profile.\n\nHe has remained functionally well overall since the prostate operation, but on further questioning he endorses urinary frequency, urgency, dysuria, weak stream, intermittent visible hematuria, and occasional episodes of incomplete emptying with brief urinary retention symptoms. He denies tobacco use currently and says he drinks alcohol only occasionally. He is retired, lives with his spouse, and has good family support. His current chronic medications are for background comorbidities only and are not considered causative treatment for the prostate malignancy."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
